CEO of a digital startup called <a href=\"http://www.magloft.com/\" target=\"_blank\">MagLoft</a>, an online software-as-a-service firm that helps independent publishers create fully branded magazines on iOS and Android, or formatted for any other web platform. “I\'m definitely able to work on MagLoft and the business from anywhere, which is very, very awesome,\" says Nick with a satisfied grin. “My true goal in life has always been to have the ability to choose when and where I work. While MagLoft is based in Bali and won\'t necessarily relocate, having had that dream from the early days, it kind of makes me a digital nomad by heart.\"[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\" css=\".vc_custom_1411479622940{padding-top: 10px !important;padding-bottom: 10px !important;background-color: #ededed !important;background-position: center !important;background-repeat: no-repeat !important;background-size: cover !important;}\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_single_image image=\"\" alignment=\"\" style=\"vc_box_rounded\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" css_animation=\"\"][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Today, with his blonde hair and blue eyes, his stellar tan, and his apparent lifestyle, Nick looks for all the world like the typical beach bum: the kind of guy who spends his days surfing and his nights playing guitar with friends around a campfire. You might not peg him as the e-business type — until you get him talking, that is. But just five years ago, Nick\'s life was a very different story. There\'s no beach in this part of the tale.\r\n\r\nAfter attending Copenhagen Business School, double-majoring in economics and computer science to graduate as computer game designer, the half-Danish half-English 20-something went straight to work at a local bank. He sat in a cubicle, crunching numbers as a retail analyst. Nick says he wasn\'t unhappy working there, but deep down he was searching for the kind of freedom that most of us only dream of as we gaze out the window and wait for the clock to strike 5 pm.\r\n\r\n“Don\'t get me wrong, it was a great job, with amazing people. I had the big salary, a ton of benefits, my own car, a nice big flat — those things were all there,\" he explains. “But at the end of the day, I just knew that the nine-to-five wasn\'t for me. Although I was having a great time, I knew that wasn\'t my future.\"[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\" css=\".vc_custom_1411479636520{padding-top: 10px !important;padding-bottom: 10px !important;background-color: #ededed !important;background-position: center !important;background-repeat: no-repeat !important;background-size: cover !important;}\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]At the time, in an effort to stay stimulated, Nick was dabbling with a few online company ideas in addition to his day job. A friend of his knew he was interested in tech startups, and introduced him to a program called <a href=\"http://www.projectgetaway.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Project Getaway</a>. “It was a 30-day event in Bali where entrepreneurs get to meet and build startups together,\" he says. “They get to live together and work together. While everyone is working on different companies, they all get to be with like-minded people, share ideas, and have the experience together.\"\r\n\r\nNick was unable to contain his excitement. He immediately reached out to the founder of Project Getaway, a fellow Danish serial entrepreneur and investor named Michael Bodekaer. When the two realized how closely their visions synced up, Nick and Bodekaer were on the next flight to Bali, and Nick\'s life — complete with nine-to-five at the bank — would never be the same.\r\n\r\nToday, along with running MagLoft full-time, Nick is also one of the senior managers of <a href=\"http://liv.it/\" target=\"_blank\">Liv.it</a>, the firm responsible for Project Getaway. Liv.it consists of nine villas in the artsy Balinese town of <a href=\"http://www.indonesia.travel/en/destination/277/ubud\" target=\"_blank\">Ubud</a>. The houses serve as accommodation and workspaces for the entrepreneurs in-residence. The firm has five full-time staff members handling the cooking and cleaning. This way, Nick says, the people who come can focus solely on building their online businesses in paradise. Nick often steps out onto his terrace with a morning coffee, only to look down and see tech founders lounging by the pool, writing code on their laptops.\r\n\r\nNick launched MagLoft in mid-2013, and claims the business has seen steady revenue growth month-on-month since its inception. It has started to pull in high-profile partners, one of which is Yahoo. MagLoft has also received some investor interest, but Nick confirms he\'d prefer to let his business grow organically for now. As such, he invites techies to submit their resumes, as MagLoft prepares for a hiring spree.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_single_image image=\"\" alignment=\"\" style=\"vc_box_rounded\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" css_animation=\"\"][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Building a Business on Your Own Terms','','inherit','closed','closed','','532-revision-v1','','','2015-10-08 06:47:13','2015-10-08 06:47:13','',532,'http://asus-zenpad.stagingapps.net/lifestyle/zenpad/2015/10/08/532-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
